const nocardiaActinomycesTopic: LibraryTopic = {
  id: 'nocardia-actinomyces',
  subjectId: 'microbiology',
  subspecialtyId: 'microbiology-gram-positive',
  name: 'Nocardia & Actinomyces',
  slug: 'nocardia-actinomyces',
  description: 'Nocardiosis, actinomycosis, sulfur granules, brain abscess',
  content: {
    concept: `# Nocardia & Actinomyces

## Overview
These are filamentous, branching Gram-positive bacteria that can mimic fungal infections. Though morphologically similar, they differ significantly in pathogenesis and treatment.

| Feature | Nocardia | Actinomyces |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Gram stain | Positive, branching | Positive, branching |
| Acid-fast | Weakly positive (modified) | Negative |
| Oxygen | Strict aerobe | Strict anaerobe |
| Habitat | Soil | Normal oral/GI flora |
| Typical patient | Immunocompromised | Immunocompetent |
| Key treatment | TMP-SMX | Penicillin |

---

## Nocardia

### Species
- **N. asteroides complex** (most common)
- **N. brasiliensis** (cutaneous, mycetoma)
- **N. farcinica** (more resistant)

### Morphology
- Gram-positive, filamentous, branching (1 μm width)
- **Weakly acid-fast** (modified Kinyoun, 1% H₂SO₄)
- "Partially acid-fast" - acid-fast for short decolorization
- Beaded appearance

### Clinical Syndromes

#### Pulmonary Nocardiosis
- Most common presentation
- Risk factors: Immunocompromised (steroids, transplant, HIV)
- Mimics TB or malignancy
- Cavitary lesions, nodules

#### CNS Nocardiosis
- **Brain abscess** (often from pulmonary spread)
- May be multiple
- Immunocompromised patients

#### Cutaneous Nocardiosis
- **Mycetoma** (N. brasiliensis) - chronic granulomatous infection
- Lymphocutaneous syndrome (sporotrichoid spread)
- Traumatic inoculation

### Diagnosis
- **Modified acid-fast stain**: Weakly positive (1% H₂SO₄)
- Culture: Slow-growing (2-4 weeks), aerobic
- "Chalky" white colonies
- CT: Ring-enhancing lesions (brain), nodules/cavities (lung)

### Treatment
- **TMP-SMX** (first-line)
- Alternatives: Amikacin, imipenem, linezolid
- Duration: 6-12 months (longer for CNS involvement)
- Immunocompromised: May need lifelong suppression

---

## Actinomyces

### Species
- **A. israelii** (most common pathogen)
- A. naeslundii, A. odontolyticus

### Morphology
- Gram-positive, branching filaments
- **NOT acid-fast** (vs Nocardia)
- Strict anaerobe
- Part of normal oral, GI flora

### Sulfur Granules
- Yellow granules in pus/tissue
- **Not sulfur** - actually clumps of organisms with calcium phosphate
- Crushed granule shows branching filaments

### Clinical Syndromes

#### Cervicofacial Actinomycosis (50%)
- "Lumpy jaw"
- Following dental procedure, tooth extraction, trauma
- Hard, non-tender swelling → draining sinuses
- Crosses tissue planes (ignores anatomical barriers)

#### Thoracic Actinomycosis (15%)
- Extension from cervicofacial or aspiration
- May involve chest wall, form sinus tracts
- Mimics malignancy or TB

#### Abdominal/Pelvic Actinomycosis (20%)
- Associated with appendicitis, bowel perforation
- **IUD-associated** (pelvic actinomycosis)
- Abscess, sinus tracts

### Diagnosis
- **Sulfur granules** in pus or tissue
- Culture: Strict anaerobic, slow (2+ weeks)
- "Molar tooth" colonies
- Biopsy often needed (mimics cancer)

### Treatment
- **Penicillin G** (high-dose IV) × 2-6 weeks, then oral × 6-12 months
- Alternatives: Amoxicillin, doxycycline
- **Surgery** may be needed for debulking, drainage

---

*"Nocardia loves the brain, Actinomyces loves to drain - through sinuses that cross every plane."*`,
    
    keyPoints: [
      'Nocardia: Weakly acid-fast, strict aerobe, soil organism',
      'Actinomyces: NOT acid-fast, strict anaerobe, normal oral flora',
      'Nocardia affects immunocompromised; Actinomyces affects immunocompetent',
      'Nocardia causes brain abscess; Actinomyces causes "lumpy jaw"',
      'Sulfur granules: Yellow granules in actinomycosis (clumps of organisms)',
      'Actinomyces crosses tissue planes - forms draining sinuses',
      'Nocardia treatment: TMP-SMX × 6-12 months',
      'Actinomyces treatment: Penicillin × 6-12 months',
      'IUD-associated pelvic actinomycosis is well-described',
      'Both may mimic malignancy or tuberculosis'
    ],
    
    examPrep: {
      summary: `**Nocardia vs Actinomyces - High Yield**

